x4freetext: Median energy in the different foils composing the
stacks was calculated using the polynomial
approximation of stopping power data proposed
by Andersen and Ziegler.
CGR-560 cyclotron
High purity natural Pt foils from Goodfellow,
thickness: 10-12.4 micron.
High purity Ge detector, Canberra Accuspec
boards and Genie 2000 acquisition/analysing software.
Detector-sample distances: 20-5 cm.
Two stacks containing 10 Pt foils were irradiated.
Primary energies of the alpha beams: 38.9 and 38 MeV,
beam intensity: 200 nA,
irradiation time: 2700 sec,
measurements started: 2 h after the end of bombardment
and continued for several weeks.
Nondestructive measurement without chemical separation.
Only for the lowest energy gamma-lines a correction for
self-absorption in the high Z, high density Pt foils
was necessary (correction factor of 1.06 for the 98 keV
line of 195gAu in 12 micron foils, factor drops to less
than 1.03 above 130 keV).
Decay data were taken from NuDat2 database.
Cu monitor foils from Goodfellow, purity > 99.6%,
thickness: 7.8 micron.
Chapter 4
Estimated uncertainty of the primary energy
of the beam is 0.2 MeV. The uncertainty in the average
energy for the last foil of the stack was estimated to
be 1.8 MeV.
The total uncertainty amounts to (8-13%)
obtained by quadratic summation of the contributing
sources.
determination of the peak areas including
statistical errors (1-5%),
number of target nuclei including
non-uniformity (5%),
incident particle intensity (5%),
detection efficiency (5%),
absolute abundance of the used gamma rays
On the basis of the new experimental cross
sections integral yields were calculated.
